`crates/steno/src/expand/` runs the four-pass pipeline that turns a parsed dictionary AST into flat `TypedEntry` records ready for rendering: resolve `@type` definitions, expand `@count` into concrete templates, append type strokes into `%t` slots, then generate one-liner variants. `mod.rs`'s `expand_dict` is the sole external entry point and fixes the pass order — `build_type_set` → `expand_counts` (Pass A) → `expand_types_one` (Pass B) → `expand_line_flag` — and this order is load-bearing: line-flag processing must see the entire batch at once (it can only run once, after all entries are typed), and later passes assume `%t`/`%b`/braces/landings are progressively resolved, not all at once.

The five files split cleanly by pass, and coupling flows through two shared record shapes plus one shared helper. `ExpandedEntry` (Pass A output, `counts.rs`) and `TypedEntry` (Pass B output, `append.rs`/`lineflag.rs`) are both defined in `mod.rs`; any field change there ripples into all three passes. `types.rs` builds the `TypeSet`/`TypeDef` pool that `fill.rs` walks to enumerate append chains (`fillings`), which `append.rs` consumes to actually splice rendered text or landings into templates via `fill_template`/`with_types`. `fill.rs` is private — its role is only discoverable through `counts.rs` or `append.rs`. `TypedEntry.terminal` (false = non-terminal step, brace/movement must be skipped downstream) and `.one_liner` (true = `%b` collapses instead of breaking) are flags set across `append.rs` and `lineflag.rs` that the downstream renderer depends on; their meaning must stay in sync with whatever consumes `Chunk` next.

Cross-cutting invariants: every pass returns `Result<_, ExpandError>` and fails fast on the first bad entry (no partial-success accumulation anywhere in the pipeline). `@type` templates are restricted to `Chunk::Lit`/`Chunk::TypeSlot` only (enforced in `types.rs`); count-related chunks (`Dcount`/`Computed`/`Repeat`) are resolved only in `counts.rs` and must not still appear afterward; `%t` slots are resolved only in `append.rs`/`fill.rs`. `ITERATION_BASE` (in `counts.rs`, re-exported publicly from `mod.rs`) fixes repeat-index numbering dictionary-wide. Fused single-slot constructs (`append.rs`) never emit a bare type-less skeleton entry, unlike normal appends.

No `intent.md` is present for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.